03933nam a22006135i 9780226706283DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226706283  a(DE-B1597)523219  a(OCoLC)802269871  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN682.C6 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a808.8035431 aReddy, William M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Making of Romantic Love :bLonging and Sexuality in Europe, South Asia, and Japan, 900-1200 CE /cWilliam M. Reddy. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (456 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Practices of Meaning00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. The Emergence of Courtly Love in Europe -- tPart Two. Points of Comparison -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Transliterated South Asian Words -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the twelfth century, the Catholic Church attempted a thoroughgoing reform of marriage and sexual behavior aimed at eradicating sexual desire from Christian lives. Seeking a refuge from the very serious condemnations of the Church and relying on a courtly culture that was already preoccupied with honor and secrecy, European poets, romance writers, and lovers devised a vision of love as something quite different from desire. Romantic love was thus born as a movement of covert resistance. In The Making of Romantic Love: Longing and Sexuality in Europe, South Asia, and Japan, William M. Reddy illuminates the birth of a cultural movement that managed to regulate selfish desire and render it innocent—or innocent enough. Reddy strikes out from this historical moment on an international exploration of love, contrasting the medieval development of romantic love in Europe with contemporaneous eastern traditions in Bengal and Orissa, and in Heian Japan from 900-1200 CE, where one finds no trace of an opposition between love and desire. In this comparative framework, Reddy tells an appealing tale about the rise and fall of various practices of longing, underscoring the uniqueness of the European concept of sexual desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCourtly love in literature. 0aCourtly love. 0aLovezEurope. 0aLovezJapan. 0aLovezSouth Asia. 0aTroubadours. 70(DE-601)1048969570(DE-588)4236084-5aRomantische Liebe2gnd 70(DE-601)1055993440(DE-588)4144301-9aBegierde2gnd 70(DE-601)10582299X0(DE-588)4114328-0aKulturvergleich2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022670626940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226706283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226706283/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles